Bluetongue -- extension of the BTV 1 and BTV 8 restriction zones
----------------------------------------------------------------
The restriction zones as related to bluetongue virus (BTV) serotypes 1 and
8 have been extended to cover the whole departments of Charente,
Charente-Maritime, Dordogne, Gironde, and Lot-et-Garonne.

The updated list of all the regulated communities/municipalities will be
sent by mail.

As of 18 Jul 2008, 6280 cases of BT disease are listed in France for the
year 2008 (of which 6 are cases of BTV serotype 1). A total of 260 BTV-8
cases of 2008 have been ascribed to viral circulation during 2008.

For information: during 2007, 15 569 BT cases have been reported (of which
3 caused by BTV-1).

--
communicated by:
Susan Baekeland
La Meurte du Ruisseau
Le Ruisseau
50240 Carnet
Lower Normandy
France
<grolleyog@tele2.fr>

[The above update includes a map showing the locations of the new outbreaks
while indicating their respective involved serotypes. The document includes
also a detailed list of the regions under BTV restrictions.

A previous French bluetongue update of 2 Jul 2008 (see posting
20080703.2027), said: "To date, 6017 cases of BT disease are listed in
France for 2008 (of which 6 are cases of BTV serotype 1). A total of 13
cases of BTV-8 of 2008 have been derived from viral circulation in 2008."

Comparing the 2 reports it may be concluded that, since 2 Jul 2008, the
number of 2008 BTV-8 cases has increased in France from 6017 to 6280 (263
added), while the number of new cases, attributed to virus circulation, has
increased from 13 to 260 (243 added). This deserves an explanation which
would be very much appreciated.

According to a report from the Bluetongue French National Reference
Laboratory (AFSSA-Alfort), dated 3 Jul 2008, only 4 isolates of BTV-8 had
been performed, until 3 Jul 2008, from samples derived during 2008 (1 in
March, 3 in June). See Zientara et al, posting 20080703.2027, item [2]. An
official update would be most welcome.

We are obliged to repeat the 2 questions included in the above posting --
which, in fact, may address all BTV-8 affected countries:
1. How many new cases, indicative of virus circulation, have been
identified during 2008?
2. Has the 2008 vector season commenced already?

Since the disease activity season is expected to start soon anyway (or has
already started?!), practitioners, veterinary inspectors, and
epidemiologists will have to deal with suspected cases and provide
advise/directions to animal breeders. We find it useful to include the 2
following abstracts from reports written by Dutch, French, Belgian, and
German investigators. The papers have just become available online as
corrected proofs of articles in press. - Mod.AS]

******
[2]
Date: Sat 19 Jul 2008
Source: article in press, corrected proof, available online, part I [edited]
<http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.prevetmed.2008.06.004>


Clinical signs in sheep and cattle in Belgium, France, and the Netherlands
(abstract)
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Starting August 2006, a major epidemic of bluetongue (BT) was identified in
north west Europe, affecting The Netherlands, Belgium, Germany, Luxemburg,
and the north of France. It was caused by BT virus serotype 8 (BTV-8), a
serotype previously unknown to the European Union (EU). In this outbreak,
the virus caused clinical disease in a few individual animals within cattle
herds, whereas overt clinical disease was usually restricted to sheep.

Investigations in Belgium suggested that the 1st clinical signs of BTV-8
appeared mid July 2006 in a cattle herd, while the 1st suspicion of a
BT-outbreak in Belgium was reported on 17 Aug 2006. In the 1st 10 BTV-8
outbreaks in the Netherlands, the owners indicated that the 1st clinical
signs started approximately 12­17 days before a suspicion was reported to
the veterinary authorities via a veterinary practitioner.

In BTV-8 affected sheep flocks, erosions of the oral mucosa, fever,
salivation, facial and mandibular oedema, apathy and tiredness, mortality,
oedema of the lips, lameness, and dysphagia were among the most frequent
clinical signs recorded. The most prominent clinical signs in BTV-8
affected cattle herds were: crusts/lesions of the nasal mucosa, erosions of
lips/crusts in or around the nostrils, erosions of the oral mucosa,
salivation, fever, conjunctivitis, coronitis, muscle necrosis, and
stiffness of the limbs.

Reference
---------
Elbers ARW, et al. Field observations during the bluetongue serotype 8
epidemic in 2006, I. Detection of 1st outbreaks and clinical signs in sheep
and cattle in Belgium, France and the Netherlands. Prev Vet Med 2008;
<http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.prevetmed.2008.06.004>

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

