[3]
Date: Sat 19 Jul 2008
Source: article in press, corrected proof, available online, part II [edited]
<http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.prevetmed.2008.06.003>


Case fatality and clinical recovery in sheep and cattle in the Netherlands
(abstract)
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Data collected in the Netherlands during the Bluetongue serotype 8 (BTV-8)
epidemic indicated that in outbreak cattle herds, predominantly dairy and
nursing cows were clinically affected and not young stock, beef cattle,
beef calves, or breeding animals. In outbreak sheep flocks, mainly ewes and
­- if present ­- rams, were clinically affected and not the lambs.

Median morbidity rate in outbreak herds was 1.85 per 100 sheep-month at
risk and 0.32 per 100 cattle-month at risk for sheep and cattle,
respectively. The mean proportion of BT-affected animals in outbreak herds
that recovered from clinical disease was approximately 8 times higher for
cattle compared to sheep in the Netherlands. Median mortality rate in
outbreak herds was 0.5 per 100 sheep-month at risk of dying and 0 per 100
cattle-month at risk of dying for sheep and cattle, respectively. Median
recovery time of both sheep and cattle that recovered from clinical disease
in outbreak herds was 14 days.

Median case fatality was 50 per cent in sheep outbreak flocks and 0 per
cent in outbreak cattle herds. It is concluded that morbidity and mortality
in outbreak cattle herds was very limited during the BTV-8 epidemic in the
Netherlands in 2006. In outbreak sheep flocks, morbidity was limited, with
exceptions for a few flocks. However, almost 50 per cent of the clinically
sick sheep died in outbreak sheep herds.

Reference
---------
Elbers ARW, et al. Field observations during the Bluetongue serotype 8
epidemic in 2006, II. Morbidity and mortality rate, case fatality and
clinical recovery in sheep and cattle in the Netherlands. Prev Vet Med
2008; <http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.prevetmed.2008.06.003>

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The above observations in both papers may serve as a helpful tool in the
dealings with new bluetongue disease outbreaks in affected countries, and
particularly in new, hitherto unaffected territories, which may be expected
within Europe and maybe elsewhere.

One comment is due: though paper II includes the statement "there were
suggestions by farmers that part of the differences in mortality rate could
be attributed to differences in sheep breeds, but we were unable to verify
this", both papers do not include any information on the animal (bovines,
ovines) breeds exposed and affected. Breed susceptibility, particularly in
sheep, is of utmost significance when clinical signs, morbidity and
mortality of bluetongue are addressed.

BTV-8 vaccination in the affected European countries seems to proceed
according to plans. In the UK, the Protection Zone will be extended again
from Mon 21 Jul 2008 to cover Worcestershire and the districts in North
Yorkshire (Scarborough, Ryedale, Hambleton and Harrogate), Cheshire
(Macclesfield, Congleton and Crewe and Nantwich) and Greater Manchester
(Rochdale, Oldham, Tameside and Stockport) previously in the Surveillance
Zone, following the delivery of 1.9 million additional doses of Bluetongue
vaccine. This is in accordance with the Bluetongue vaccination plan in the UK.

A map showing the most recent update (18 Jul 2008) locations of the
restriction zones in Europe is available at
<http://ec.europa.eu/food/animal/diseases/controlmeasures/bluetongue_restrictedzones_.jpg>.
- Mod.AS]
